anyOf.description:
dimensionHeight
Define the min and max Y bounds of this dimension. Please keep in mind that Iris internally generates from 0 to (max - min). 

For example at -64 to 320, Iris is internally generating to 0 to 384, then on outputting chunks, it shifts it down by the min height (64 blocks). The default is -64 to 320. 

The fluid height is placed at (fluid height + min height). So a fluid height of 63 would actually show up in the world at 1.
   
Range (Object)
Represents a range
    
You can instead specify "snippet/range/some-name.json" to use a snippet file instead of specifying it here.
    
* Default Value is a default object (create this object to see default properties)

oneOf.description: No interpolation. Nearest Neighbor (bad for terrain, great for performance).
Uses 4 nearby points in a square to calculate a 2d slope. Very fast but creates square artifacts. See: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bilinear_interpolation

Starcast is Iris's own creation. It uses raytrace checks to find a horizontal boundary nearby. 3 Checks in a circle. Typically starcast is used with another interpolation method. See BILINEAR_STARCAST_9 For example. Starcast is meant to 'break up' large, abrupt cliffs to make cheap interpolation smoother.

See BILINEAR_STARCAST_9 For example. Starcast is meant to 'break up' large, abrupt cliffs to make cheap interpolation smoother.

mode.description:
mode
Add = add on top of parent tables, Replace = clear first then add these. Clear = Remove all and dont add loot from this or parent.
   
LootMode
A loot mode is used to describe what to do with the existing loot layers before adding this loot. Using ADD will simply add this table to the building list of tables (i.e. add dimension tables, region tables then biome tables). By using clear or replace, you remove the parent tables before and add just your tables.
    
* Default Value is a default object (create this object to see default properties)
Must be a valid LootMode (use ctrl+space for auto complete!)
